<br>
I’ve been wracking my brain for some improvements I could suggest for the Wizard class.<br>
<br>
<br>
Suggestion One.<br>
<br>
At Level 34, we gain a great advantage for the Wizard Class: Harvest. This spell has been said to not scale properly after Level 50. Is this still the case? If so, that is the first fix I could suggest. That, or at Level 44 add a new spell Harvest II which has the same stats as Harvest I but returns 300-500 manna. And possibly add at 54 Harvest III. Again, same stats, but returns 600 manna. Or maybe make Harvest into a Skill, that way a spell slot may not be wasted with memorising a spell which many over Level 50 deem as a wasted slot. If it were a skill, people would continue to use it since it would no longer be rotting in a spell-slot. Perhaps add a Level 59 AA for Wizards: Ultimate Harvest. Refresh every 15 minutes, returns 500 manna. Similar to the Shaman AA skill Cannibalisation.<br>
<br>
<br>
Suggestion Two.<br>
<br>
Wizards are fabled to be the Masters of Direct Damage. This is just an off-the-cuff idea, but why not grant Wizards access to the NPC specific nukes. We already have the Porlor’s Fury and Hsargra’s Wrath spells which are NPC specific.<br>
<br>
How about the DD Vs. Summoned and Undead NPCs? These are harder to resist (supposedly) and more manna efficient than our regular nukes until the higher levels when the difference is negligible.<br>
<br>
Level 8: Ward Summoned/Undead<br>
Level 16: Expulse Summoned/Undead<br>
Level 24: Dismiss Summoned/Undead<br>
Level 34: Expel Summoned/Undead<br>
Level 44: Banish Summoned/Undead<br>
Level 55: Exile Summoned/Undead<br>
Level 60: Banishment/Banishment of Shadows<br>
<br>
It’s just a thought. This probably wouldn’t have much room for abuse since we get an all-purpose Banishment spell at Level 60, but the inherent bonuses of having NPC specific spells would apply. I’m sure not everyone will like this, but I think it’s a good idea since it isn’t really giving us better nukes at later levels, but just ones which are harder to resist (I think).<br>
<br>
<br>
Suggestion Three.<br>
<br>
I, along with many other Wizards, feel there is something missing. Wizards are one of the few magic based classes who cannot lower the resistance of their targets. The only other classes who cannot do this are the Cleric, the Paladin, the Shadow-Knight and the Beastlord. Three of these four classes are Hybrids and it is rarely their place to receive assistance in resistance debuffing. Magicians have infiltrated the realm of Shamen and acquired the Malise line of spells, decreasing Magic, Poison, Cold and Heat resistances even though they only receive spells in two of these four areas. The only consolation for Wizards is a quest which can be completed with some difficulty past Level 24. The Staff of Temperate Flux. However, the effect is not the greatest influence. At Level 24, Magicians can debuff 4 out of 5 resistances by roughly 18 points each with the expenditure of a small amount of manna. Wizards have a manna-free click effect which debuffs Heat and Cold by six points which is enough to notice a minor change in the ability for wizard’s spells to hit for more damage than usual. There is no debuffing of Magic Resistance, so this stick is rendered useless when trying to use the Level 20 DD spells like Force Shock and Garrison’s Mighty Manna Shock let alone the most widely used line of all: Root.<br>
<br>
I would like to make a suggestion for a new spell line.<br>
<br>
Since there is such a spell as remove Greater Curse now, and Wizards being loosely based on the occult (buzz-words like familiars and female wizards being referred to as witches by Alhakazham), then why not give them a weak curse line of spells?<br>
<br>
Say, for example,<br>
Level 16. Minor Curse: lowers Magic, Cold and Heat resistances by 10 each. 75 manna.<br>
Level 29: Lesser Curse: lowers Magic, Cold and Heat resistances by 20 each. 140 manna.<br>
Level 44: Curse: lowers Magic, Cold and Heat resistances by 30 each. 205 manna.<br>
Level 60: Greater Curse: lowers Magic, Cold and Heat resistances by 20 each (un-resistible). 280 manna.<br>
<br>
All but the Level 60 spell can be dispelled with the cancel magic line, but for interest make the Level 60 spell only dispellable with Remove Greater Curse. Other than that, it would last its normal five-minute (or so) duration.<br>
<br>
For argument’s sake, let’s make it not stack with any other magic/cold/heat debuff just like the Staff of Temperate Flux. They are quite manna heavy, that being a penalty for the Wizard getting the debuff. Also, why not give it a large casting time? Say, the same as Ice Comet or so? 7 seconds would make it less useful in a sudden ambush scenario.<br>
<br>
<br>
Suggestion Four (or 3.2)<br>
<br>
If the Curse line is not appealing, then I would suggest a minor change to the Staff of Temperate Flux. Change the click level to 30 and make it debuff Magic, Heat and Cold by 20. Give it a casting time (this will annoy those who use it for distance-judgement) and make it equippable in the Range Slot (equipped click-activation only). This would force players to choose between a ranged item and the Staff of Temperate Flux (aside from the right click, it would add the +5 Save vs. Cold/Heat).<br>
<br>
<br>
Suggestion Five.<br>
<br>
How about making the spell “Spell-Shield” a group spell like Blessing of Aegolism and Boon of the Garou. Maybe up the manna and reagent cost accordingly. This would just be to minimise the amount of manna/time Wizards have to spend buffing others. Since we’ve never had to do so before, we would want to get it over and done quickly. Then it would also make sense to give the Wizard the mass-group buff AA skill, since Magicians get it solely for their Aegis of Ro spell, we may as well get it for our Spell-Shield <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Suggestion Six.<br>
<br>
I like the idea of keeping Sunstrike as the most manna efficient DD Wizards get, but I would like to see the addition of a Level 59 AA skill which raises further the chance of Specialising in an Evocation-based spell. Or possibly allowing another Specialise Skill to exceed the 50 cap and raise to 100 or so. This would be helpful in the only other field where Wizards have essential combat spells: Alteration. So we would have Specialise Evocation at over 200, Specialise Alter at 100 and the other three (Divination, Abjuration and Conjuration) at 50.<br>
<br>
<br>
Suggestion Seven.<br>
<br>
Druids get the Class AA skill Enhanced Root which lowers the risk of breaking root with DD by 50%. I would like to see Wizards granted this ability too since we are more dependant and more specialised in Root skills than Druids, even if theirs has a DD component. We may get Strong Root, but I would still like to see Enhanced Root added. This would enhance our root spells in general, not just an emergency root once an EQ-Day.<br>
<br>
<br>
As you’re well aware these are just some random ideas thrown out by an idle player, but I do think that this is an area that Wizards have been overlooked.<br>
<br>
Comments? HELPFUL criticisms? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/utargonis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/7/02 10:08:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=659.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Some new ideas for Wizard spells/skills etc. Comments pl</span><hr size=1> Another thing they could do would be to make some of the current arch and class specific AA skills into NORMAL skills available at an appropriate level.  AA skills are a nice idea for those of us who are level 60 already, but many things like being able to land a spell crit should have been wizard skills/abilities all along.<br>
